{
  "Homeostasis refers to:": "",
  "The absence of all body regulation": "",
  "Maintenance of stable internal conditions": "",
  "Unlimited cell growth": "",
  "Constant change in the body": "",
  "Homeostasis is the body's ability to maintain a relatively stable internal environment (such as temperature, pH, and blood glucose) despite changes in external conditions.": "",
  "Most feedback loops in the human body are:": "",
  "Neutral feedback": "",
  "Absent entirely": "",
  "Negative feedback": "",
  "Positive feedback": "",
  "Negative feedback is the most common regulatory mechanism in the body because it reverses changes and restores conditions to their set point, which is essential for maintaining homeostasis.": "",
  "Negative feedback works by _____ the original stimulus.": "",
  "Ignoring": "",
  "Amplifying": "",
  "Reversing or reducing": "",
  "Doubling": "",
  "Negative feedback opposes the direction of the initial change, effectively reversing or reducing the stimulus to bring the variable back toward its set point.": "",
  "Body temperature regulation is an example of:": "",
  "Homeostatic failure": "",
  "No feedback mechanism": "",
  "When body temperature rises above 37 degrees C, sweating and vasodilation are triggered to cool the body down; when it drops, shivering and vasoconstriction warm it up. This reversal of the change is classic negative feedback.": "",
  "Blood clotting is an example of:": "",
  "Homeostasis failure": "",
  "No feedback": "",
  "Blood clotting is a positive feedback mechanism because each clotting factor activates more clotting factors, amplifying the response until the wound is completely sealed.": "",
  "The three components of a feedback loop are:": "",
  "Input, storage, and output": "",
  "Brain, heart, and lungs": "",
  "Receptor, control center, and effector": "",
  "Stimulus, gene, and enzyme": "",
  "Every feedback loop consists of a receptor (sensor) that detects the stimulus, a control center (usually the brain or an endocrine gland) that processes the information, and an effector (muscle or gland) that carries out the response.": "",
  "Normal body temperature is approximately:": "",
  "42 degrees C (107.6 degrees F)": "",
  "37 degrees C (98.6 degrees F)": "",
  "35 degrees C (95 degrees F)": "",
  "40 degrees C (104 degrees F)": "",
  "The homeostatic set point for core body temperature is approximately 37 degrees C (98.6 degrees F), and the body uses feedback mechanisms to maintain temperature near this value.": "",
  "Insulin is released when blood glucose is:": "",
  "Normal": "",
  "High": "",
  "Absent": "",
  "Low": "",
  "When blood glucose rises above normal (such as after a meal), beta cells of the pancreas release insulin, which promotes glucose uptake by cells and lowers blood glucose levels back to normal.": "",
  "The effector in a feedback loop is the component that:": "",
  "Detects the change in the environment": "",
  "Processes the incoming information": "",
  "Carries out the corrective response": "",
  "Creates the initial stimulus": "",
  "The effector is the component (typically a muscle or gland) that executes the corrective action in response to commands from the control center, such as sweat glands cooling the body or the pancreas releasing insulin.": "",
  "If homeostasis fails, the result can be:": "",
  "Disease or death": "",
  "No consequence": "",
  "Stronger feedback mechanisms": "",
  "Improved health": "",
  "When homeostatic mechanisms fail or are overwhelmed, the body can no longer maintain stable internal conditions, leading to disease, disorder, or in severe cases, death.": "",
  "What is negative feedback?": "",
  "A mechanism that amplifies the original stimulus until a process is completed": "",
  "A mechanism that ignores all changes in the internal environment": "",
  "A mechanism that reverses or opposes the direction of change to restore a variable to its set point": "",
  "A mechanism that only operates during sleep": "",
  "Negative feedback is a regulatory mechanism in which the output of a process opposes or reverses the initial stimulus, effectively shutting down the response once the set point is reached, such as thermoregulation or blood glucose regulation.": "",
  "What is positive feedback?": "",
  "A mechanism that amplifies the original stimulus, pushing the variable farther from the set point until a process is completed": "",
  "A mechanism that opposes the stimulus to restore balance": "",
  "A mechanism that only functions in the digestive system": "",
  "A mechanism that maintains a constant internal temperature": "",
  "Positive feedback enhances or amplifies the original change rather than reversing it. It is less common than negative feedback and typically drives a process to completion, such as during childbirth or blood clotting.": "",
  "What is a receptor in a feedback loop?": "",
  "A sensor or structure that monitors the environment and detects changes (stimuli)": "",
  "A hormone released into the blood": "",
  "The organ that carries out the corrective response": "",
  "The brain center that sends out commands": "",
  "A receptor (sensor) is the component of a feedback loop that detects a change in a physiological variable, such as thermoreceptors in the skin sensing temperature changes or baroreceptors sensing blood pressure changes.": "",
  "What is a set point?": "",
  "The normal target value around which a physiological variable is regulated": "",
  "The lowest value a physiological variable can reach": "",
  "A point at which all feedback stops permanently": "",
  "The maximum value a physiological variable can reach before death": "",
  "A set point is the ideal or normal value that the body works to maintain for a given physiological variable, such as 37 degrees C for body temperature or approximately 90 mg/dL for fasting blood glucose.": "",
  "What does 'control center' mean in a feedback loop?": "",
  "The muscle or gland that carries out the response": "",
  "The processing center (often the brain or an endocrine gland) that evaluates input and determines the appropriate response": "",
  "The stimulus that initiates the feedback loop": "",
  "The sensor that detects environmental changes": "",
  "The control center receives information from receptors, compares it to the set point, and sends commands to the effector to make corrections. The brain (especially the hypothalamus) and endocrine glands commonly serve as control centers.": "",
  "What does 'effector' mean in the context of feedback mechanisms?": "",
  "The chemical signal sent between the receptor and brain": "",
  "A structure that detects changes in the internal or external environment": "",
  "A structure (muscle or gland) that receives signals from the control center and produces a response to correct the imbalance": "",
  "The set point value the body tries to maintain": "",
  "An effector is the component of the feedback loop that carries out the corrective action, such as skeletal muscles (shivering to generate heat) or sweat glands (producing sweat to cool the body).": "",
  "What is the role of glucagon in blood glucose regulation?": "",
  "It has no effect on blood glucose": "",
  "It raises blood glucose by stimulating the liver to release stored glycogen as glucose": "",
  "It destroys glucose molecules": "",
  "It lowers blood glucose by promoting glucose uptake into cells": "",
  "Glucagon is a hormone released by alpha cells of the pancreas when blood glucose drops too low. It stimulates the liver to break down glycogen into glucose and release it into the blood, raising blood glucose levels.": "",
  "What is a fever in terms of homeostatic regulation?": "",
  "The same thing as heatstroke": "",
  "An example of positive feedback leading to death": "",
  "A complete failure of all homeostatic mechanisms": "",
  "A deliberate resetting of the body's temperature set point to a higher value by the hypothalamus": "",
  "During an infection, pyrogens cause the hypothalamus to raise the temperature set point, so the body actively generates heat (shivering, vasoconstriction) until the new, higher set point is reached. This is a regulated adjustment, not a loss of homeostasis.": "",
  "What is the stimulus in a feedback loop?": "",
  "The response produced by the effector": "",
  "The signal sent from the control center to the effector": "",
  "A change in a physiological variable that triggers the feedback mechanism": "",
  "The set point value the body maintains": "",
  "A stimulus is any change in a controlled variable (such as a rise in body temperature or a drop in blood glucose) that is detected by a receptor and initiates the feedback loop to restore homeostasis.": "",
  "What does 'homeostatic imbalance' mean?": "",
  "A condition in which the body's feedback mechanisms can no longer maintain stable internal conditions, often leading to disease": "",
  "The process of positive feedback during childbirth": "",
  "A temporary increase in heart rate during exercise": "",
  "The normal fluctuation of body variables within a healthy range": "",
  "Homeostatic imbalance occurs when feedback mechanisms are disrupted, overwhelmed, or absent, causing internal conditions to deviate significantly from normal and often resulting in disease or pathological states.": "",
  "A patient arrives at the emergency room with a core body temperature of 35 degrees C after prolonged exposure to cold weather. The medical team observes uncontrollable shivering. In this scenario, the shivering skeletal muscles are acting as the:": "",
  "Receptor": "",
  "Effector": "",
  "Control center": "",
  "Stimulus": "",
  "In the thermoregulatory feedback loop, skeletal muscles act as the effector by shivering (rapid involuntary contractions) to generate heat and raise the body temperature back toward the 37 degrees C set point.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a case in which a pregnant woman's labor contractions become progressively stronger. The student recognizes that oxytocin stimulates uterine contractions, which push the baby against the cervix, causing more oxytocin release. This is an example of:": "",
  "A feedback loop with no effector": "",
  "Positive feedback amplifying the stimulus until delivery": "",
  "Homeostatic failure requiring medical intervention": "",
  "Negative feedback restoring homeostasis": "",
  "Childbirth is a classic example of positive feedback: oxytocin causes contractions, contractions push the baby against the cervix, the cervix signals for more oxytocin, and the cycle amplifies until the baby is delivered and the stimulus is removed.": "",
  "A nurse observes that after a diabetic patient receives an insulin injection, the patient's blood glucose level drops from 250 mg/dL to 100 mg/dL. This therapeutic intervention mimics which type of natural feedback mechanism?": "",
  "A feedback mechanism that increases blood glucose": "",
  "The insulin injection mimics the body's natural negative feedback for glucose regulation: when blood glucose is high, insulin is released to lower it. The response (glucose dropping) opposes the stimulus (high glucose), restoring the variable toward its set point.": "",
  "During a physiology lab, a student exercises vigorously and notices her heart rate increases and she begins to sweat. After she stops exercising, her heart rate and sweating gradually return to normal. This return to baseline demonstrates:": "",
  "Failure of the thermoregulatory system": "",
  "Permanent elevation of the set point": "",
  "Negative feedback restoring homeostasis after the stimulus is removed": "",
  "Positive feedback amplifying the exercise response": "",
  "Once the exercise stimulus is removed, negative feedback mechanisms work to restore heart rate and body temperature to their normal set points, demonstrating the body's ability to re-establish homeostasis.": "",
  "A patient with Type 1 diabetes cannot produce insulin. Without medication, this patient's blood glucose would remain dangerously elevated. This situation represents:": "",
  "A homeostatic imbalance due to a broken negative feedback loop": "",
  "Positive feedback enhancing glucose levels": "",
  "The body's normal response to a high-sugar diet": "",
  "Normal negative feedback functioning properly": "",
  "In Type 1 diabetes, the immune system destroys the beta cells of the pancreas, eliminating the body's ability to produce insulin. Without this effector component, the negative feedback loop for glucose regulation is broken, resulting in chronic hyperglycemia.": "",
  "A nursing student is caring for a patient who has been out in 40 degrees C heat for several hours. The patient has stopped sweating, has hot dry skin, and a core temperature of 41 degrees C. The student recognizes this as heatstroke. Why has the normal thermoregulatory system failed?": "",
  "The body's cooling mechanisms have been overwhelmed, creating a dangerous positive feedback loop": "",
  "The patient's set point was permanently lowered": "",
  "Negative feedback is still functioning normally": "",
  "The patient has too much insulin in the blood": "",
  "In heatstroke, the body's cooling mechanisms (sweating, vasodilation) are overwhelmed by extreme heat. As core temperature rises, enzymes begin to denature and thermoregulatory mechanisms fail further, creating a dangerous positive feedback loop where rising temperature accelerates the breakdown.": "",
  "A patient cuts their finger while cooking. Almost immediately, a cascade of clotting factors begins to seal the wound. Each clotting factor activates more clotting factors. A medical student identifies this as positive feedback because:": "",
  "The body returns to normal immediately without any amplification": "",
  "The response has no effect on the stimulus": "",
  "The response opposes the original stimulus": "",
  "Each step in the process amplifies the next until the wound is sealed": "",
  "Blood clotting is positive feedback because each activated clotting factor triggers the activation of more factors, amplifying the clotting cascade until the wound is completely sealed and the stimulus (blood vessel damage) is resolved.": "",
  "A physician explains to an anatomy class that when blood pressure drops suddenly, baroreceptors in the carotid arteries detect the change, the brain processes this information, and the heart beats faster. In this scenario, the baroreceptors are acting as the:": "",
  "Stimuli": "",
  "Control centers": "",
  "Effectors": "",
  "Receptors": "",
  "Baroreceptors are specialized sensory receptors that detect changes in blood pressure. In this feedback loop, they serve as the receptor component by sensing the drop in pressure and sending signals to the brain (control center), which then directs the heart (effector) to increase its rate.": "",
  "A patient recovering from surgery develops a fever of 38.5 degrees C. The attending physician explains that the hypothalamus has temporarily raised the temperature set point in response to infection. A nursing student asks why the patient is shivering despite having a fever. The best explanation is:": "",
  "The patient's current body temperature is below the new, higher set point, so the body generates heat through shivering to reach it": "",
  "Shivering indicates the temperature set point has been lowered": "",
  "The feedback loop has completely failed": "",
  "The patient is experiencing heatstroke": "",
  "During a fever, pyrogens cause the hypothalamus to raise the temperature set point. If the body's current temperature is below this new set point, the body activates heat-generating mechanisms like shivering and vasoconstriction until the higher target is reached.": "",
  "A physiology professor presents a case where a person eats a large meal and blood glucose rises to 140 mg/dL. The pancreas releases insulin, which causes cells to absorb glucose, bringing blood glucose back to 90 mg/dL. The professor asks students to identify all three components of this feedback loop in order. The correct sequence is:": "",
  "Control center (muscles) â†’ Receptor (skin) â†’ Effector (heart)": "",
  "Receptor (pancreatic beta cells detect high glucose) â†’ Control center (pancreas determines response) â†’ Effector (liver and body cells take up glucose)": "",
  "Stimulus (insulin) â†’ Receptor (stomach) â†’ Effector (brain)": "",
  "Effector (beta cells) â†’ Control center (liver) â†’ Receptor (muscles)": "",
  "In blood glucose regulation, the pancreatic beta cells act as both receptor and control center by detecting elevated glucose and releasing insulin. The effectors are the body's cells (especially liver, muscle, and fat cells) that respond to insulin by taking up glucose from the blood.": ""
}